In Manatee County, FL we are looking at this as well. We have a very large service area for our utilities, but have no real criteria for line extensions within that area. We end up with longer distances of lines without customers hooked up along roadways. We are proposing the following in the Land Development Code for a future amendment, but still needs to be vetted by our Public Works Engineering staff and refined more. 
705.1.  Extension of County Central Potable Water and Sanitary Sewer Service.
a.  The Comprehensive Plan allows requires Special Approval of extensions of the utility system within the service area. The following Special Approval criteria applies to these requests. The following is the criteria for approval which shall include analysis of the following factors:
(1) Extension of lines must be within existing County Utilities Service Areas; 
(2) Logical extension of utilities away from plants or infill development;
(3) Extensions within ½ mile of current lines;
(4) Project not consistent with State definition of Urban Sprawl;
(5) Consistent with Comprehensive Plan and other elements of this Code;
(6) Consistent with the Manatee County Sewer Collection Ordinance;
(7) Provides less than 1,200 feet of distance without existing or new customer hookups;
(8) Consistent with timing and trends of area of county; and
(9) Provides redundancy in overall utility system plan;  or
(10)    Project already approved prior to this policy; or
(11)    Part of approval of Development of Regional Impact.
John Osborne, AICP
Planning & Zoning Official
Manatee County, FL
john.osborne@mymanatee.org
941-748-4501 x7425


